# Testing Standards (Playwright + Cucumber)

## Architecture Decision

- Playwright Test is the primary framework for API, session injection, contract, token, and integration coverage.
- Cucumber BDD is used only for a small set of business-readable end-to-end journeys.
- Do not convert the entire framework to Cucumber.
- Required coverage split:
  - ~70% API + session injection + contract validation
  - ~20% UI verification of authenticated state and key widgets
  - ~10% system-wide end-to-end journeys in Cucumber
- Refactor in place only: reuse existing helpers/selectors/page objects/auth utilities/specs and avoid duplicate suites.

## Framework Structure

```text
playwright/
  api/
    auth/
    payments/
    wallet/
    cards/
    payment-links/
  ui/
    auth/
    dashboard/
    payment-links/
    transactions/
  e2e/
    features/
    step-definitions/
    support/
  helpers/
  fixtures/
  schemas/
```

- `api/` and `ui/` remain Playwright Test.
- `e2e/features` and `e2e/step-definitions` use Cucumber for true cross-system business flows only.
- Step definitions stay thin; business logic lives in page objects/helpers.

## Authentication Strategy

- Keep auth pyramid at 70/20/10.
- Default path for non-E2E:
  - authenticate via API
  - inject token/session into browser context
  - reuse authenticated state across UI tests
- Only true E2E scenarios should use full login UI.

## Required Environment Variables

- `BASE_URL`
- `API_URL`
- `AUTH_API_LOGIN_PATH`
- `TEST_EMAIL`
- `TEST_PASSWORD`
- `LOCKED_USER_EMAIL`
- `LOCKED_USER_PASSWORD`
- `SUSPENDED_USER_EMAIL`
- `SUSPENDED_USER_PASSWORD`
- `DELETED_USER_EMAIL` (if backend supports deleted-account auth behavior)
- `DELETED_USER_PASSWORD` (if backend supports deleted-account auth behavior)
- `UNVERIFIED_USER_EMAIL` (if backend supports unverified-account auth behavior)
- `UNVERIFIED_USER_PASSWORD` (if backend supports unverified-account auth behavior)
- `MFA_USER_EMAIL`
- `MFA_USER_PASSWORD`
- `AUTH_LOCKOUT_PROBE_EMAIL`
- `AUTH_LOCKOUT_PROBE_PASSWORD`
- `STRICT_AUTH_CONTRACT`

## Authentication Coverage

- Ensure auth layer covers:
  - valid login
  - wrong password
  - missing email/password
  - invalid email format
  - leading/trailing spaces
  - email case sensitivity
  - empty vs null vs omitted values
  - long input values
  - SQL injection attempts
  - XSS attempts
  - locked/suspended/deleted/unverified/MFA-enabled users
  - lockout/cooldown
  - token refresh/logout/session validation
  - expired/tampered token rejection
- Keep API negatives production-realistic in API tests; keep client-side blocked flows asserted in UI tests.

## Strict Auth Contracts

- Every auth assertion must validate:
  - HTTP status code
  - domain/error code
  - message
  - response schema/shape
  - sensitive fields are absent
- Never allow these fields in auth responses:
  - `password`
  - `passwordHash`
  - `secret`
  - `internalNotes`
- Success contract baseline:
  - `expect(response.status()).toBe(200)`
  - `expect(body).toMatchObject({ success: true, accessToken: expect.any(String), refreshToken: expect.any(String) })`
- Locked contract (`STRICT_AUTH_CONTRACT=true`):
  - `expect(response.status()).toBe(403)`
  - `expect(body).toMatchObject({ code: 'ACCOUNT_LOCKED', message: expect.any(String) })`
- Suspended contract (`STRICT_AUTH_CONTRACT=true`):
  - `expect([401, 403]).toContain(response.status())`
  - `expect(body).toMatchObject({ code: expect.stringMatching(/ACCOUNT_SUSPENDED|UNAUTHORIZED/), message: expect.any(String) })`

## MFA / 2FA Standard

- Login response must match backend contract:
  - `expect(body).toMatchObject({ success: true, message: '2FA code sent to registered email', requires2FA: true, userId: expect.any(String) })`
  - `expect(body.accessToken).toBeUndefined()`
  - `expect(body.refreshToken).toBeUndefined()`
- Capture `userId` and reuse for OTP verification.
- OTP verify success must return:
  - `expect(verifyOtpBody).toMatchObject({ success: true, accessToken: expect.any(String), refreshToken: expect.any(String) })`
- Negative OTP scenarios (if not already covered):
  - invalid OTP
  - expired OTP
  - reused OTP
  - missing OTP
  - missing userId
  - wrong userId
  - too many OTP attempts
  - OTP resend rate limit
- If mailbox integration is missing, skip OTP-dependent specs gracefully.

## Token and Session Requirements

- Ensure coverage for:
  - access token existence
  - refresh token existence
  - JWT structure validity
  - refresh token rotation invalidates old token
  - logout invalidates token
  - protected/session endpoint rejects invalid token
  - expired token rejection
  - tampered token rejection

## API-First Principle

- All non-UI setup must use API helpers:
  - login
  - account/test-data creation
  - payment-link creation
  - wallet setup
  - transfer setup
  - transaction setup
- Do not use UI for preconditions unless validating that UI workflow.

## Financial Validation Rules

- For payment/transfer/wallet/card/payment-link flows always validate:
  - amount
  - currency
  - balance before/after
  - status
  - timestamp
  - history/audit entry
  - UI consistency with API
- Release blockers:
  - incorrect balance
  - missing transaction
  - duplicate transaction
  - incorrect status
  - silent failure
  - empty history after successful action

## UI Automation Standards

- Selector priority:
  1. `data-testid`
  2. `aria-label`
  3. role + visible text
  4. semantic attributes
- Never use:
  - dynamic Chakra hashed selectors
  - `nth-child`
  - index-based selectors
  - deep CSS selector chains
- If no stable selector exists, require a `data-testid`.
- For each UI action, assert:
  - page/header correctness
  - visible feedback message
  - enabled/disabled state
  - redirect/navigation correctness
  - updated values on screen
  - consistency with backend response

## Global UI Interruptions

- Implement reusable handlers for:
  - cookie banner
  - notification popup
  - session timeout modal
  - "Your New BizFlex Card Awaits" modal
  - new card modal
- Modal handling must:
  - re-check visibility before clicking
  - tolerate detach/re-render
  - avoid hashed selectors unless no stable alternative exists

## Waiting Strategy

- Never use fixed waits as the primary synchronization strategy.
- Use:
  - API/network completion
  - spinner/skeleton disappearance
  - visible/hidden state transitions
  - explicit response completion checks

## Payment Link Standard

- Keep payment-link pyramid at 70/20/10.
- API coverage includes:
  - create general link
  - create unique link
  - fetch by uid
  - fetch published/draft
  - update link
  - update settings
  - validate counts
  - initiate order
  - confirm order
  - retrieve requests
- Always validate:
  - amount
  - currency
  - reference
  - link URL
  - status
  - timestamp
  - response schema
- UI coverage remains focused on:
  - dashboard loads
  - copy action works
  - modal opens
  - success modal shows generated link
  - published/draft list visible
  - dashboard count matches API

## CI and Stability Standards

- Tests must run independently and in parallel.
- Only lockout/cooldown flows may run serial:
  - `test.describe.serial('lockout flow', () => { ... })`
- Lockout tests must use dedicated probe accounts only.
- If probe vars are missing, skip lockout tests (do not fail suite).
- Retry strategy:
  - `retries: process.env.CI ? 1 : 0`
- Preserve failure artifacts:
  - `trace: 'retain-on-failure'`
  - `screenshot: 'only-on-failure'`
  - `video: 'retain-on-failure'`
- On failure, log:
  - request payload
  - response body
  - headers
  - correlation ID (if available)
  - relevant UI state snapshot

## Cucumber Usage

- Use Cucumber only for high-value business journeys, e.g.:
  - sign in -> transfer -> verify balance and transaction history
  - create payment link -> customer pays -> dashboard reflects transaction
  - request card -> card appears -> wallet reflects card transaction
  - suspended user attempts restricted action and gets restriction message
- Example feature names:
  - `money-transfer.feature`
  - `payment-link-payment.feature`
  - `wallet-balance-update.feature`
  - `restricted-account.feature`
- Do not move simple validation, API contracts, token checks, negative field validation, or lockout edge cases into Cucumber.

